hands_on_practices.solution:
We are given $X=\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & -a \end{pmatrix}$ with real $a,b,c$ satisfying $a^{2}+bc=0$. First compute $X^{2}$ explicitly:
$$
X^{2}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a & b \\ c & -a
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
a & b \\ c & -a
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a^{2}+bc & ab-ab \\
ca-ac & cb+a^{2}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a^{2}+bc & 0 \\
0 & a^{2}+bc
\end{pmatrix}
=(a^{2}+bc)I.
$$
Using the given condition $a^{2}+bc=0$, we obtain $X^{2}=0$. By the power series definition of the matrix exponential,
$$
\exp(tX)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{(tX)^{n}}{n!}=I+tX+\frac{t^{2}}{2!}X^{2}+\cdots.
$$
Since $X^{2}=0$, all terms of order $n\geq 2$ vanish, hence
$$
\exp(tX)=I+tX.
$$
Therefore,
$$
\exp(tX)=\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
+
t\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & -a \end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1+at & bt \\
ct & 1-at
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
